<i>Merret</i>, a syncopated form of <i>Margaret</i>, <i>Mergeret</i>."]}]},{"name":"Herbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":14,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Herbert Meriot was born in 1368, in England, his father, Edwin Meriot, was 24 and his mother, Ema G Smith, was 19. He married Sue Dell Neely in 1387, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1417, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1368–about 1417":"1368–umbes 1417","1368–1417":"1368–1417","1368–1393":"1368–1393","1389–1415":"1389–1415","1345–1367":"1345–1367","1350–1367":"1350–1367","12 July 1393":"12. juuli 1393","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1415":"1415","about 1417":"umbes 1417","1368":"1368","1367":"1367","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1387":"1387","about 1389":"umbes 1389","1417":"1417","after 1367":"pärast 1367","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1368–about 1417":"1368–noin 1417","1368–1417":"1368–1417","1368–1393":"1368–1393","1389–1415":"1389–1415","1345–1367":"1345–1367","1350–1367":"1350–1367","12 July 1393":"12. heinäkuuta 1393","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1415":"1415","about 1417":"noin 1417","1368":"1368","1367":"1367","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1387":"1387","about 1389":"noin 1389","1417":"1417","after 1367":"1367 jälkeen","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"1368–about 1417":"1368–environ 1417","1368–1417":"1368–1417","1368–1393":"1368–1393","1389–1415":"1389–1415","1345–1367":"1345–1367","1350–1367":"1350–1367","12 July 1393":"12 juillet 1393","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1415":"1415","about 1417":"environ 1417","1368":"1368","1367":"1367","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1387":"1387","about 1389":"environ 1389","1417":"1417","after 1367":"après 